%pyspark

data = sc.textFile("/data/santander-customer-transaction-prediction/train.csv").filter(lambda x: not x.startswith('ID')).map(lambda x: x.split()).map(lambda x: x[0].split(','))
label = data.map(lambda x: int(x[1]) )
feature = data.map(lambda x: x[2:])

from pyspark.mllib.linalg import Vectors
from pyspark.mllib.feature import StandardScaler

scaler = StandardScaler(withStd=True, withMean=True).fit(feature)

from pyspark.mllib.regression import LabeledPoint
feature_sc = scaler.transform(feature)
feature_sc.take(5)
data_sc=label.zip(feature_sc).map(lambda x: LabeledPoint(int(x[0]),x[1]) )

%pyspark
seed=2
(training_data,test_data)=data_sc.randomSplit([0.8, 0.2] ,seed)
print( training_data.count() )
print( test_data.count() )

%pyspark

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

from pyspark.mllib.regression import LinearRegressionModel, LinearRegressionWithSGD
from pyspark.mllib.classification import LogisticRegressionWithLBFGS, LogisticRegressionModel
from pyspark.mllib.classification import SVMModel, SVMWithSGD
from pyspark.mllib.regression import LassoModel, LassoWithSGD

SVM= SVMWithSGD.train(data_sc)

%pyspark
Preds = SVM.predict(test_data.map(lambda x: x.features.toArray()))

%pyspark
##Evaluate Model
labelsAndPreds=test_data.map(lambda x: x.label ).zip(Preds.map(lambda x: float(x))).cache()
testErr = labelsAndPreds.filter(lambda (x,y): y != x).count() / float(labelsAndPreds.count())
print("Training Error = " + str(testErr))

%pyspark
from pyspark.mllib.evaluation import BinaryClassificationMetrics

print(labelsAndPreds.take(50))
auc= BinaryClassificationMetrics(labelsAndPreds).areaUnderROC

print("Areau under the roc: " + str(auc) )

class CurveMetrics(BinaryClassificationMetrics):
    def __init__(self, *args):
        super(CurveMetrics, self).__init__(*args)

    def _to_list(self, rdd):
        points = []
        # Note this collect could be inefficient for large datasets 
        # considering there may be one probability per datapoint (at most)
        # The Scala version takes a numBins parameter, 
        # but it doesn't seem possible to pass this from Python to Java
        for row in rdd.collect():
            # Results are returned as type scala.Tuple2, 
            # which doesn't appear to have a py4j mapping
            points += [(float(row._1()), float(row._2()))]
        return points

    def get_curve(self, method):
        rdd = getattr(self._java_model, method)().toJavaRDD()
        return self._to_list(rdd)
        
roc = CurveMetrics(labelsAndPreds).get_curve('roc')

plt.figure()
x_val = [x[0] for x in roc]
y_val = [x[1] for x in roc]

title='roc curve'
plt.title(title)
#plt.xlabel(xlabel)
#plt.ylabel(ylabel)
plt.plot(x_val, y_val)

from pyspark.mllib.tree import GradientBoostedTrees, GradientBoostedTreesModel
from pyspark.mllib.util import MLUtils

# Train a GradientBoostedTrees model.
#  Notes: (a) Empty categoricalFeaturesInfo indicates all features are continuous.
#         (b) Use more iterations in practice.
model = GradientBoostedTrees.trainClassifier(training_data,
                                             categoricalFeaturesInfo={}, numIterations=100)

# Evaluate model on test instances and compute test error
predictions = model.predict(test_data.map(lambda x: x.features))
labelsAndPreds = test_data.map(lambda lp: lp.label).zip(predictions)
testErr = labelsAndPreds.filter(
    lambda lp: lp[0] != lp[1]).count() / float(test_data.count())
print('Test Error = ' + str(testErr))
print('Learned classification GBT model:')
print(model.toDebugString())

from pyspark.mllib.evaluation import BinaryClassificationMetrics

print(labelsAndPreds.take(50))
BinaryClassificationMetrics(labelsAndPreds).areaUnderROC

class CurveMetrics(BinaryClassificationMetrics):
    def __init__(self, *args):
        super(CurveMetrics, self).__init__(*args)

    def _to_list(self, rdd):
        points = []
        # Note this collect could be inefficient for large datasets 
        # considering there may be one probability per datapoint (at most)
        # The Scala version takes a numBins parameter, 
        # but it doesn't seem possible to pass this from Python to Java
        for row in rdd.collect():
            # Results are returned as type scala.Tuple2, 
            # which doesn't appear to have a py4j mapping
            points += [(float(row._1()), float(row._2()))]
        return points

    def get_curve(self, method):
        rdd = getattr(self._java_model, method)().toJavaRDD()
        return self._to_list(rdd)
        
roc = CurveMetrics(labelsAndPreds).get_curve('roc')

print(roc)
